The 15-month requirements to get the social welfare Christmas bonus has been reduced to four months

text.69:
Social welfare: 

Package worth total €510 million 

Increasing living alone allowance by €5 to €19 

Fuel allowance up to €28 per week 

Qualified child payment increase by €5 for over 12s and €2 for under 12s
text.70:
€9 billion for Department of Education, with €2 billion for supporting children with special educational needs

Hiring 990 additional SNAs and 403 additional teaching posts
text.71: McGrath said the climate crisis is the great challenge of our generation
text.72:
Michael McGrath said the carbon tax is not designed to raise income for the government 

An additional €100m of carbon tax revenue will be used for investment into the energy efficiency of homes
text.73:
An extra €55 million will be allocated for the tourism business support scheme

€50 million will be given towards live entertainment support 

€130 million to the Arts Council, up from €50m last year

text.99: Carbon tax will be increased by €7.50, from €26 to €33.50 per tonne. This will be applied to auto fuels from tonight and all other fuels from 1 May next year
text.100: Broadband is now included in the working from home allowances
text.101: 'Tittle tattle' was used as evidence to convict Patrick Quirke of murdering Bobby Ryan, Court of Appeal hears https://t.co/TNybGGPZYW
text.102: However, the limit for the the second USC rate band will be increased from €20,484 to €20,687 income per year
text.103: Donohoe confirms the government will not make any broad changes to income tax credits or bands in the Budget
text.104:
Donohoe said he will work to develop a tax credit for the digital gaming sector

He said this is a sector which has seen "exponential global growth"
text.105: The VAT rate for hospitality and tourism sector will reduce from 13.5% to 9% with effect from 1 November
text.106:
A targeted scheme for businesses that have been closed generally in Level 3 and higher and will be removed when restrictions are lifted 

Payments will be made on average weekly turnover - a cash payment will be made and is effective from today until 31 March
text.107:
The employment wage subsidy scheme is set to continue until next year

"There will be no cliff edge to this vital scheme," Donohoe said
text.108: Donohoe said debt warehousing provisions will be extended to the self-employed to include the 2019 balance and 2020 preliminary tax to delay payments for a year with no interest. 3% interest will apply after
text.109:
The government will set up a recovery fund worth €3.4 billion to provide resources for government decisions next year to stimulate increased domestic demand and employment 

It will be a flexible fund to provide govt with the means to react swiftly to a changing environment
text.110:
Donohoe said the total Budget package is €17.75 billion 

The impact of it will be "felt in every household and business" across the country, he adds
text.111: The Department of Finance will publish an analysis of the 2021 Budget to provide "clear evidence" of its progressive nature, Paschal Donohoe said
text.112: The country will fully utilise the €1.5 billion rainy day fund
text.113: Donohoe said the 2021 Budget projects a deficit of €20.5 billion
text.114:
Donohoe said this is a step towards a future that seems so much better than seems possible today

He said it is the time for hope that recognises our challenges
text.115: The Department of Finance is projecting a total loss of approx 320,000 jobs in 2020, recovering by approx 155,000 jobs next year
text.116:
Next year's budget has been prepared against a background of "extraordinary" circumstances, Donohoe said

This has been well flagged, but it's framed on the basis of a no-deal Brexit and no available vaccine for Covid-19 next year
text.117: The government understands the trade off in public health choices and appreciates the impact of decisions on life and livelihoods, Donohoe said https://t.co/RKiMRkjN3C
text.118:
Minister Donohoe said the country is meeting this with greater resources and support from the EU along with the "hard work, dedication and resilience of the Irish people"

He said the test we face is daunting, but "we will prevail"
text.119:
Donohoe said it's not enough for the budget to surmount immediate threats, it must make progress on priorities in society.

These are: More homes, improved, healthcare and a better national response to climate change.
text.120:
It begins. 

Paschal Donohoe says last year's budget confronted the main challenge facing Ireland - a hard Brexit. 

However, the government is now responding to the pandemic
